
[1]crow

   CROW, n. [G., L.]

   1. A large black fowl, of the genus Corvus; the beak is convex and
   cultrated, the nostrils are covered with bristly feathers, the tongue
   is forked and cartilaginous. This is a voracious fowl, feeding on
   carrion and grain, particularly maiz, which it pulls up, just after it
   appears above ground.

   To pluck or pull a crow, is to be industrious or contentious about a
   trifle, or thing of no value.

   2. A bar of iron with a beak, crook or two claws, used in raising and
   moving heavy weights.

   3. The voice of the cock. [See the Verb.]

     CROW, v.i. pret. and pp. crowed; formerly, pret. crew. [Gr. See the
                                   Noun.]

   1. To cry or make a noise as a cock, in joy, gaiety or defiance.

   2. To boast in triumph; to vaunt; to vapor; to swagger. [A popular, but
   not an elegant use of the word.]
